## Section 3 — The Stream and Content

### The Structure

Three scheduled writing streams per week are the backbone. They prove the brand's core claim — writer who writes every day — and they do it without stealing time from the writing, because the streams are the writing. That is the load-bearing insight of the whole content strategy. The fourth stream each week is gaming: community building, personality, the other half of what the brand is.

The writing streams run in Notion — the same workspace Evan writes in off stream. There is no "stream version" of the work. Viewers see the actual document, the actual process, the actual cursor moving through the actual mythology. AI tools appear on screen as they are used — as a voice and sounding board, never for the actual writing. Viewers are watching the real thing, not a curated performance of it.

Monthly public update videos are not gated. They serve as rooting interest recruitment — a straight look at how the month went, what moved, what didn't. These are the pieces most likely to bring new people in via recommendation.

### Building the B-Roll Archive

Evan has been screen recording his use of Claude and Notion over the past several days — capturing the brand and project evolving in real time. These recordings serve as raw material for timelapse sequences, b-roll footage for edited videos, and documentation of the building process itself. The screen recordings are not planned content — they're ambient capture. When a video needs to show the process behind the process, the footage is already there.

This is consistent with the brand's core premise: you can watch a world get made. The building started before the stream did.

### Outside Inn — The Atmosphere Layer

Outside Inn is not a separate brand. It is the atmosphere layer of the E.I. Werner world — the community gathering space, the ambient identity of the channel, and the hearth that stays lit when Evan is not live.

When Evan is not streaming, the EIW YouTube channel runs the Outside Inn lo-fi loop: original music composed by Carson Thatcher, pixel art animation by Marwan Hasnaoui, scrolling member names during warmup. The channel is a location. Sometimes the writer is behind the bar. Sometimes it is just the music and the fireplace. Either way, the door is open.

Every live stream opens and closes with the Outside Inn warmup and cooldown. Patron names scroll. It sets the tone and rewards membership visibly. Viewers who find the lo-fi stream and write or study to it for weeks before ever seeing Evan live are not cold when he goes live. They already feel like they have been sitting in his room.

The Outside Inn also names the community's Discord server. The inn is the conceptual frame: warm, inviting, a place people return to.

