## Section 5 — Collaborator Philosophy

### How This Works With People

Evan leads. He is the boss and the creative director of this brand — not a committee, not a collective. Decisions move through him. The vision is his. But he is also building the kind of operation he wished existed when he was younger: somewhere a person can do real work, be trusted with real responsibility, and share in what gets built if it succeeds.

That means backend participation. Artists whose work sells product should have a stake in what they helped build. This is not standard practice in creator merch. It is the right practice. When the brand wins, the people who built it win. The principle is non-negotiable. The exact structures — flat fees, small percentages per sale, hybrid models — will be figured out honestly and responsibly as the brand develops revenue. The commitment is to find arrangements that are fair to collaborators and financially sustainable for the operation, not to make promises the budget can't keep. Getting this right matters more than getting it right immediately.

He pays artists. Not AI. Marwan is doing the pixel art. Luiz is doing the digital painting and learning the Twitch overlay work. Carson composed the Outside Inn music. These are real people doing real creative work and they are compensated as such. AI is used for writing support and brand thinking — as a voice and sounding board — but the creative output that carries the brand belongs to humans.

He wants to be relied upon. When he says something will happen, it happens. When a collaborator is on deadline, they hear from him. When there is a problem, he addresses it directly rather than letting it fester. The Carson situation earlier this year was a lesson in what goes wrong when stress turns into clinical distance — the recovery worked because the foundation was real, but the lesson is to lead with warmth first, not after the damage is done.

The aspiration is simple: to be the boss and mentor he never had. Someone who gives real creative people real opportunities, pays them fairly, includes them in the upside, and treats the collaboration as a relationship worth protecting.

