## Section 9 — Looking Ahead

### E.I. HQ — Notion Command Center

Evan writes in Notion. On stream and off stream. The myths, the worldbuilding, the brand planning, the project management — all of it lives in Notion. He just built a clean new workspace while recording his stream setup and it looks exactly the way it should. Organizing information in Notion is one of the parts of this work he genuinely loves. Not every part of building a brand lights him up — but this part does. That matters because the things that generate real energy are the things that sustain.

E.I. HQ is the advanced Notion project that houses everything: decisions, timelines, collaborator notes, brand iterations, stream planning, the ONCE mythology, the writing itself. It serves two purposes simultaneously. First, it keeps the operation organized — one place for everything, built by someone who genuinely knows how to use Notion at a high level. Second, it is the long play for a Notion sponsorship or partnership. Streaming with Notion visibly open on screen three times a week, combined with documented mastery of the tool and real connections to leverage, makes the sponsorship conversation a real one when the viewership is there.

The long play is important and it feels right. Not strategic-right — belly-fire-right. Evan is not performing Notion use for a camera. He is a writer who writes in Notion, building a world in Notion, organizing an 18-year creative endeavor in Notion, and streaming the whole thing live. That's not a pitch. That's just what's happening. The story builds itself over time, and when the viewership justifies the conversation, the proof will already be months or years deep on camera.

### Notion Partnership or Sponsorship

This is not a cold play. Evan ran Notion company-wide at SKIMS for two and a half years. He brought SKIMS on as a paid Notion customer and became the internal champion for the tool across the organization. Through that work he developed real relationships with people at Notion — including Monica Perez (former Head of Customer Success, now at Lovable), Paige Haefer (former Mid-Market AE, now at Blockit AI), and Peter Escartin (Solutions Engineer, still at Notion). These aren't LinkedIn connections — they're people he built genuine camaraderie with over years of working together. Most have moved on from Notion; some are still there. All are still connected.

That history plus the visible Notion use on stream three times a week makes the sponsorship conversation a real one when the viewership justifies it. The approach is patience, not outreach — let the body of work on camera speak first, and when the time comes, the relationships are already there.

### Virtual Currency & Watch Time Rewards

Viewers earn virtual currency by watching — time in stream translates directly into unlockable rewards. The longer you stay, the more you accumulate. Currency can be spent on channel emotes and chat emojis, creating an incentive to watch that is tied to the experience itself rather than a purchase. This rewards genuine presence over transactions and gives non-paying viewers a meaningful way to participate and feel invested in the community.

### Sustainable Album Model

Carson delivered roughly 100 minutes of original music for the Outside Inn lo-fi loop. That's the proof of concept. The music exists, the animation exists, the station runs. What comes next is the repeatable model.

The angle: Evan genuinely enjoys finding young, unknown artists and channeling their talent into something real. The Outside Inn taught him what it takes to produce an album's worth of original lo-fi music with original pixel art — and the answer is sub-$7,500. Closer to $5k if he's disciplined about it. Approximately 14 tracks, original animation, emerging creatives given a real opportunity and a piece of the upside.

The economics are simple. Each album needs to earn itself back through a combination of streaming revenue, merch featuring the album art (deskmats, posters, mousepads), and the Fourthwall store. If the art is good — and it should be, because that's the whole point of working with real artists — it sells. Each album funds the next. The catalog grows. The art appreciates. The loop never goes stale.

This is not a priority for the beta period. Carson's music covers the launch and then some. But the model is there when the time comes: find artists with something to prove, give them a platform and backend participation, make something together that neither could make alone, and build a catalog that compounds over years. Every collaborator who comes through gets something real — a credit, an audience, and a stake in what gets built.

### Machinima

WoW machinima remains a genuine curiosity — learning a new medium in public, telling stories inside a game engine. It's not prioritized for the beta period. If and when it happens, it happens because the energy is there and the timing is right. It is not a pillar of the content strategy. It is a playground.

